related_questions.question: What is flour made of?
related_questions.snippet: Flour is made during a grinding process called “milling.” Milling is the grinding of wheat kernels, also called “berries.” During the milling process, the three parts of the wheat grain (bran, germ and endosperm) are separated and recombined to make the different types of wheat flours.

related_questions.question: What's the healthiest flour?
related_questions.snippet: Whole-wheat flour is much heartier than all-purpose flour and produces denser baked goods with a more robust flavor. Milled from wheat berries with the nutritious bran and germ still intact, whole-wheat flour is rich in fiber and essential micronutrients like iron, magnesium and vitamin B6.

related_questions.question: What are the four types of flour?
related_questions.snippet: Professional bakes understand that achieving a consistent product is much more likely if you use the same type of flour each time for a particular recipe. Depending on the dish, these typically include all-purpose flour, cake flour, pastry flour, self-rising flour and bread flour.

buttons.title: 11 best flour substitutions - BBC Good Food
buttons.snippet: Rice, potato, tapioca, maize and buckwheat are just some of the common grains that you might find in a gluten-free flour blend. These combination flours usually work best in cakes, biscuits and pastry. In most cases, you should be able to swap plain flour for the same amount of gluten-free flour in a recipe.

buttons.subtitle: Protein In Flour
buttons.title: Protein percentage in flour: Why it matters | King Arthur Baking
buttons.snippet: Bread flour: With a protein percentage of 12.7%, this is considered a high-protein flour. It has more gluten-forming potential; when you mix dough made with bread flour rather than all-purpose, more protein is present, and as a result, the dough will likely develop more gluten.
